                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d266">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Gresham</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-01-25">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 25, 1895</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your 374 received. Act 1890 provides that it shall take effect at a time to be
                    fixed by the President, by proclamation issued for that purpose. The President
                    issued proclamation declaring that act should go into force March 1, the effect
                    being the same as if the act had declared it should take effect on that date;
                    and the President’s power in the matter is exhausted.</p>
            </div>
